            "bib": {
                "title": "Hippocampal neurogenesis regulates forgetting during adulthood and infancy",
                "cites": "5746205500028235248",
                "year": "2014",
                "url": "https://science.sciencemag.org/content/344/6184/598.abstract",
                "author": "Katherine G Akers and Alonso Martinez-Canabal and Leonardo Restivo and Adelaide P Yiu and Antonietta De Cristofaro and Hwa-Lin Liz Hsiang and Anne L Wheeler and Axel Guskjolen and Yosuke Niibori and Hirotaka Shoji and Koji Ohira and Blake A Richards and Tsuyoshi Miyakawa and Sheena A Josselyn and Paul W Frankland",
                "journal": "Science",
                "volume": "344",
                "number": "6184",
                "pages": "598-602",
                "publisher": "American Association for the Advancement of Science",
                "abstract": "Throughout life, new neurons are continuously added to the dentate gyrus. As this continuous addition remodels hippocampal circuits, computational models predict that neurogenesis leads to degradation or forgetting of established memories. Consistent with this, increasing neurogenesis after the formation of a memory was sufficient to induce forgetting in adult mice. By contrast, during infancy, when hippocampal neurogenesis levels are high and freshly generated memories tend to be rapidly forgotten (infantile amnesia), decreasing neurogenesis after memory formation mitigated forgetting. In precocial species, including guinea pigs and degus, most granule cells are generated prenatally. Consistent with reduced levels of postnatal hippocampal neurogenesis, infant guinea pigs and degus did not exhibit forgetting. However, increasing neurogenesis after memory formation induced infantile amnesia in these \u2026",
                "eprint": "https://www.scienceintheclassroom.org/sites/default/files/research-papers/science-2014-akers-598-602.pdf"
            },
